# Introduction {#introduction}

This runbook provides a detailed, step-by-step guide for taking over an existing Kubernetes cluster. The outcome of this process, referred to as “takeover,” enables Palette to adopt and manage an existing cluster, providing the same comprehensive management capabilities as it does for clusters initially deployed by Palette.

Rather than being a specific feature, *takeover* is provided as a framework to achieve the desired outcome, which is to have a brownfield cluster fully managed by Palette or Palette VerteX.

The following outcomes describe the purposes of this document:

* Identify the logistics of a takeover process.  
* Actionable, documented takeover plan.  
* Guide the users through taking over an existing cluster with Palette.  
* Optimize and reduce the risk of subsequent takeovers.

## Audience {#audience}

This document is intended for the person(s) that will be responsible or participate in the takeover process.   
It is written assuming the person using these procedures is familiar with the source clusters and their configurations, Kubernetes, Palette, or Palette VerteX.

## Scope & Out of Scope

To complete:

* backup

## Glossary {#glossary}

* **Takeover**: Process in which Palette or Palette VerteX adopts and integrates an existing Kubernetes cluster that Palette did not initially deploy. The takeover process allows Palette to manage the cluster as if Palette initially provisioned it. Data and workloads remain intact and operational during the takeover, though a maintenance window is required to ensure a smooth transition.  
* **Source Cluster**: Kubernetes cluster that is undergoing the takeover process to be adopted and managed by Spectro Cloud’s Palette platform. Although referred to as a “source cluster,” it remains the same cluster at the end of the process. The cluster is transformed to be managed by Palette without any actual migration.  
* **Adopted Cluster**: A Kubernetes cluster that has completed the takeover process and is now fully managed by Spectro Cloud’s Palette platform. The adopted cluster retains its original data and workloads but is transformed to leverage Palette’s management capabilities, ensuring enhanced operational efficiency and control.  
* **Maintenance Windows**: A scheduled period during which a cluster undergoes maintenance activities to ensure a smooth transition during the takeover process. During the maintenance window, no changes are allowed to the cluster to prevent disruptions and ensure data integrity. Additionally, no external interaction with the cluster is desired to maintain stability and minimize potential issues, even from the application teams.  
* **Infrastructure Profile**: Infrastructure profiles provide the essential components for workload cluster deployments within a tenant: Operating System (OS), Kubernetes, Network, and Storage. Collectively, these layers form the infrastructure for your cluster. For more information, review the Create an Infrastructure Profile guide.  
  * Documentation: [Cluster Profiles](https://docs.spectrocloud.com/profiles/cluster-profiles/)

## About this Document

* Although this document will refer solely to Palette from now on, both Palette and Palette VerteX support the takeover process, and the steps are applicable to both editions.

# Takeover Process {#takeover-process}

The takeover methodology is decoupled into 6 phases, as depicted below.

|  | Phase | Description |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| 1 | **Readiness Assessment** Assess the source environment  configuration, common to a complete takeover project | The readiness assessment phase aims to analyze the customer’s environment and develop a detailed, executable runbook for the takeover of a cluster or a list of clusters. This involves evaluating the current state of the Kubernetes clusters and the organization’s readiness for the takeover process. This step may be common for a group of clusters. **Expect Outcome**: A comprehensive assessment report detailing the cluster’s readiness for takeover, highlighting any gaps or necessary preparations. |
| 2 | **Discovery & Cloud Preparation** Relevant to a group of clusters | This phase involves discovering and documenting the existing cluster’s configurations, resources, and dependencies. Additionally, it includes preparing the cloud environment to support the cluster's integration with Palette. This step may be common for a group of clusters. **Expected Outcome**: A functional Palette instance ready with specific requirements and configurations, including cluster profiles and cloud accounts configured. |
| 3 | **Pre-takeover Readiness & Preparation** Specific to 1 cluster | This phase focuses on preparing one individual cluster and its associated resources for the takeover process. It includes ensuring backups are in place, verifying configurations, and setting up any necessary tools or scripts. The step is specific to one cluster. The maintenance window starts at the end of this phase. **Expected Outcome**: All necessary tools and scripts are in place, and the cluster is correctly modeled for its cloud and Kubernetes configurations. |
| 4 | **Takeover Inception** Initiates the actual takeover process | This phase initiates the actual takeover process to integrate the existing cluster into Palette. It involves registering the cluster component in Palette. **Expected Outcome**: Successful initiation of the takeover process, with a cluster registered in Palette, though still in a *Provisioning* status. |
| 5 | **Onboarding & Rollout** Pivot, installation of agents and reconciliation | This phase includes initializing the source cluster with Cluster API (CAPI), transferring CAPI resources to the workload cluster, applying the agent manifests, and the automatic reconciliation through Palette. **Expected Outcome**: The cluster is fully onboarded into Palette, with all features and configurations applied, and operational management transitioned to Palette. |
| 6 | **Validation & Cleaning** Functional validation, cleaning of old and temporary resources | This final phase involves validating the success of the takeover process. It includes thorough testing to ensure that all workloads and data remain intact and operational. Additionally, it involves cleaning up any outdated or temporary resources used during the transition. **Expected Outcome**: Validation of a successful takeover, with the cluster operating seamlessly under Palette’s management and all temporary resources cleaned up. |

Considerations:

* Spectro Cloud does not have visibility into the applications running on the cluster; the takeover process focuses solely on the Kubernetes cluster management and infrastructure.  
* All workloads operating on the designated source Kubernetes cluster(s) are expected to adhere to cloud-native principles, such as the elimination of Single Point of Failure (SPOF): Spectro Cloud will not be responsible for any workload downtime resulting from workload misconfigurations, failure to adhere to these principles, or the presence of SPOF.  
* Only the infrastructure profile will be covered in the takeover process; existing add-ons will have to be modeled later by the customer as a follow-up action.  
* No changes to the configuration of the source cluster are permitted during the takeover process.  
* No Kubernetes upgrades will be performed during the takeover process.  
* If the source cluster uses an external etcd for Kubernetes, after the takeover, etcd will be transitioned to a stacked topology running on the control plane nodes.  
* Any additional etcd nodes used by other components in the Kubernetes cluster (e.g., an external etcd for Calico) will remain intact and will not be affected during the takeover process.  
* No Container Network Interface (CNI) or Container Storage Interface (CSI) migrations will occur during the takeover process.  
* For non-CAPI-based source clusters (such as kubeadm), additional costs may be incurred until the cluster is fully transitioned into Palette as we grow first by creating new control plane and new worker nodes, which has an impact on:  
  * Infrastructure capacity and technical requirements (IP availability)  
  * Cost  
* Adopted clusters will be of a specific AWS type, which should only be used for clusters undergoing the takeover process.  
* As of today (October 2024), cluster autoscaler is not supported for clusters undergoing the takeover process. Therefore, the cluster autoscaler must be disabled prior to initiating the takeover.

# Preparation & General Requirements {#preparation-&-general-requirements}

The requirements outlined in this section are standard to a complete takeover project.

* Required Palette version: The required Palette version for the takeover operation is 4.5.4.  
  * Please note that this requirement is subject to change, depending on further development and tests realized in the customer environment.  
* Required Palette permissions:  
  * For the *Discovery & Cloud Preparation* phase: Access to the Palette management interface with system console privileges using an [Operations Administrator](https://docs.spectrocloud.com/enterprise-version/system-management/account-management/#operations-administrator) user.  
  * For the remaining takeover phases, sufficient permissions are required to interact with cluster profiles and create clusters.  
* Takeover control tower machine: this is where the takeover operations will be run from.  
  * Can be the bootstrap machine in case of CAPI source cluster.  
* Access Requirements:  
  * Admin access to the existing Kubernetes cluster (with kubectl). This includes access to the management and workload clusters in the case of CAPI-based source clusters.

* For non-CAPI source clusters, sufficient infrastructure resources to accommodate an increased number of nodes. We grow node pools first (for non-CAPI source clusters, such as kubeadm-based).

# Takeover Step by Step {#takeover-step-by-step}

The takeover process within Palette is provided as a comprehensive framework designed to facilitate the seamless integration of existing Kubernetes clusters into Palette’s management umbrella.  
This framework adopts a phased approach, ensuring meticulous planning, execution, and validation at each stage. By breaking down the process into distinct phases, we aim to provide a structured and methodical path that ensures minimal disruption to your operations and maximizes the effectiveness of the takeover.

## Readiness Assessment {#readiness-assessment}

The purpose of the readiness assessment phase is to analyze the customer’s environment and develop a detailed, executable runbook for the takeover of a cluster or a list of clusters. This involves evaluating the current state of the Kubernetes clusters and the organization’s readiness for the takeover process.

***Scope**: this phase is common to a complete takeover project.*

This phase aims to develop a deep understanding of all the existing clusters in scope, including how they are deployed, their ecosystem, and the specific nuances of the environment. This involves thoroughly assessing the current cluster environment, documenting configurations, workloads, and dependencies. Additionally, it focuses on identifying potential challenges and risks associated with the takeover process and determining whether the clusters are similar enough to allow for a uniform approach.

The specific steps in this phase may vary depending on the project and the customer’s governance. Typical steps include:

* Conducting interviews with relevant stakeholders.  
* Collecting architectural diagrams and relevant documentation.  
* Gathering any available code or automation scripts used for cluster deployment.  
* Analyzing Kubernetes configurations and workloads by connecting to the source clusters and reviewing existing resources, CRDs, installed operators, etc.  
* Identifying cluster dependencies and assessing the overall environment.

## Discovery & Cloud Preparation {#discovery-&-cloud-preparation}

This phase involves discovering and documenting the existing cluster’s configurations, resources, and dependencies. Additionally, it includes preparing the cloud environment to support the integration of the cluster with Palette. 

***Scope**: this phase will most likely be common to a series of clusters that will undergo the takeover process. For example, create a single cluster profile that N clusters will leverage or a cloud account in Palette.*

|  | Step | Context | Description | Validation |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| 1 | Palette Validation | All type of source clusters | Ensure that the instance of Palette where the adopted cluster will be running is healthy and at the expected version. | Palette is running the required version defined in the [Preparation & General Requirements](#preparation-&-general-requirements) section. Validate the global isHealthy \== True when accessing the /v1/mgmt/app/health Palette API   All the hubble pods in the hubble-system namespace must be running. All Kubernetes pods and nodes are up and running in the Palette Kubernetes (management) cluster. User must be able to login into the Palette system console as a system operator.  |
| 2 | AWS Cloud Registration | All type of source clusters | Register the AWS cloud type that will be used to takeover existing cluster (refer to the steps below in the [AWS Cloud Registration](#aws-cloud-registration) section). | The AWS TKO cloud type is present in Cloud Accounts in Palette. |
| 3 | Self-hosted PCG Deployment | All type of source clusters | Deploy a self-hosted private cloud gateway in AWS (refer to the steps below in the [Self-hosted PCG Deployment](#self-hosted-pcg-deployment) section). | The PCG is deployed, running, and in a healthy state. Access to the source cluster and to Palette is required from this PCG.  |
| 4 | Cloud Account Configuration | All type of source clusters | Create the cloud account in Palette (refer to the steps below in the [Cloud Account Configuration](#cloud-account-configuration) section). | The AWS account is created in the relevant Palette project. |
| 5 | Build OS Image | All type of source clusters | (Optional, only if required) If you don’t have any existing appropriate CAPI OS image, create an image to use for the cluster takeover (refer to the steps below in the [Build OS Image](#build-os-image) section). | Image is created and uploaded in the appropriate registry, available for consumption. [https://image-builder.sigs.k8s.io/capi/providers/aws](https://image-builder.sigs.k8s.io/capi/providers/aws)  |
| 6 | Registry & Packs | All type of source clusters | (Optional, only if required) Configure the appropriate registries and ensure the appropriate packs are present to configure the cluster profile in the next step. | Relevant packs are present and available for selection in a cluster profile. All packs are kept in a private Spectro Cloud registry and are not public. We can provide the binaries and they have to be hosted in one of customer’s registry. |
| 7 | Cluster Profile Configuration | All type of source clusters | Create an infrastructure profile that matches the cluster(s) that will be taken over (refer to the steps below in the [Cluster Profile Configuration](#cluster-profile-configuration) section). | The infrastructure profile is created and aligned with the target cluster’s specifications. |
| 8 | Test Cluster Deployment | All type of source clusters | Validation includes the creation of a cluster in the target cloud: test a cluster deployment from Palette in the target cloud region and AZ with said cluster profile. | The test cluster is successfully deployed, running, and healthy. Note: If the test cluster cannot be successfully deployed, the option to use the Validator to validate policies and quotas is available. |
| 9 | Backup & Restore | All type of source clusters | Using the identified existing backup system, backup the test cluster and validate that the restoration is working. | Successful backup and restore. *Note: this test cluster can be destroyed after validation.* |

### AWS Cloud Registration {#aws-cloud-registration}

Note: the version of the Kubernetes Cluster API Provider AWS (CAPA) depends on the source cluster type. For:

* Tanzu Kubernetes Grid (TKG) 2.2 on AWS clusters, CAPA 2.0.2 must be used  
* Kubeadm-based clusters, CAPA 1.5.23 must be used

CAPA 2.0.2 for TKG 2.2 Clusters

- [CAPA v2.0.2 \- infrastructure-components.yaml](https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/cluster-api-provider-aws/releases/download/v2.0.2/infrastructure-components.yaml)  
- [CAPA v2.0.2 \- cluster-template.yaml](https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/cluster-api-provider-aws/releases/download/v2.0.2/cluster-template.yaml)

CAPA 1.5.2 for Kubeadm-based Clusters

- [CAPA v1.5.2 \- infrastructure-components.yaml](https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/cluster-api-provider-aws/releases/download/v1.5.2/infrastructure-components.yaml)  
- [CAPA v1.5.2 \- cluster-template.yaml](https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/cluster-api-provider-aws/releases/download/v1.5.2/cluster-template.yaml)

The steps to register a custom AWS Cloud is similar to the process described in SpectroCloud docs \- [Register Nutanix Cloud](https://docs.spectrocloud.com/clusters/data-center/nutanix/register-nutanix-cloud/). Please note the following.

- providerID is set using aws:///\<availability-zone\>/\<instance-ID\>  
- Within CAPA yaml files there are no ConfigMaps, Secrets, or MachineHealthChecks, this is expected and does not impact the takeover.

Palette leverages CAPI 1.5.3, which is compatible with both versions of CAPA.

Requires tenant operator user

Attention to short name (use some naming convention for takeover because of pack constraints): I suggest using AWS TKO and awstko.

Once the PCG is running, the AWS cloud account must be added to Palette in the appropriate project. 

Name must be all lowercase.

\- export AWS\_REGION=\<region\>  
\- export AWS\_ACCESS\_KEY\_ID=\<your-access-key\>  
\- export AWS\_SECRET\_ACCESS\_KEY=\<your-secret-access-key\>  
\- export AWS\_SESSION\_TOKEN=\<session-token\>  
\- export AWS\_B64ENCODED\_CREDENTIALS=$(clusterawsadm bootstrap credentials encode-as-profile)

Using ‘AWS\_B64ENCODED\_CREDENTIALS’ as the AWS Account Credentials within Palette VerteX.

There are two instances of Cloud Account Configuration?

### Build OS Image {#build-os-image}

An AWS Cluster API (CAPI) OS image is required. For guidance on creating the image if it doesn’t exist yet, refer to [Building CAPI Images for AWS](https://image-builder.sigs.k8s.io/capi/providers/aws).

### Cluster Profile Configuration {#cluster-profile-configuration}

An infrastructure cluster profile created for the AWS TKO cloud created in a previous step is required. At the Cloud Type step of profile creation, select AWS TKO.

Layers must be:

* **CSI**: select the appropriate CSI layers that matches the clusters existing configuration.  
* **CNI**: select the appropriate CNI layers that matches the clusters existing configuration.  
* **Kubernetes**: mandatory selection of “*Kubernetes for Custom Cloud*”  
  * No configuration is required in that layer; Kubernetes configuration is handled separately at cluster registration.  
* **OS**: mandatory selection of “*Operating System for Custom Cloud*”  
  * No configuration is required in that layer; OS configuration is handled separately at cluster registration.

## Pre-takeover Readiness & Preparation {#pre-takeover-readiness-&-preparation}

Now that everything is ready for a group of clusters, this phase focuses on preparing one individual cluster and its associated resources for the takeover process. It includes ensuring backups are in place, verifying configurations, and setting up any necessary tools or scripts. This step is specific to one cluster, and the maintenance window starts at the end of this phase.

***Scope**: this phase and the subsequent phases are relevant to the adoption of a single cluster.*

|  | Step | Context | Description | Validation |
| ----- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| 1 | Prerequisites | All type of source clusters | Verify that all general prerequisites are met. | All requirements outlined in the [Preparation & General Requirements](#preparation-&-general-requirements) section have been validated. |
| 2 | Takeover Control Tower Machine Preparation | All type of source clusters | Takeover steps should be run from a Linux device with connectivity to the existing source management and workload clusters and to Palette.. From now on, this machine will be referred to as the takeover control tower machine.  | Validate that you have SSH access to the control tower machine. The following CLI must be installed and ready: kubectl clusterctl drivectl The takeover-templates folder takeover-templates/clusterctl.yaml must be present The overrides directory For the drivectl binary and the required manifests, please see the [Access to Takeover Artifacts](#access-to-takeover-artifacts) below. Do a screenshot with *tree / folder structure*? |
| 3 | Cluster Identification | All type of source clusters | Identify the cluster you wish to take over and collect the associated Kubeconfig files. | The appropriate cluster has been identified, and the Kubeconfig for both the source management and workload clusters has been retrieved. |
| 4 | Access to the Control Plane | Kubeadm-based source clusters | (optional) Only for non-CAPI-based source cluster Some information is required from the control plane nodes, such as PKI or admin Kubeconfig file. | Validate that you have SSH access to one of the control plane nodes (running the Kube API component) Within that control plane node, ensure access to: The admin Kubeconfig file (most likely /etc/kubernetes/admin.conf). The /etc/kubernetes/pki/ folder and its content. |
| 5 | Node Instances | Kubeadm-based source clusters | (optional) If the source Kubernetes clusters run external etcd nodes, then etcd operates on separate nodes from the control plane. The takeover process will result in a Kubernetes cluster with stacked control plane nodes, where etcd used by Kubernetes is colocated with the control plane nodes. As such, we must consider the additional performance requirements and identify new instance sizes and storage needs. Additionally, if the worker nodes require resizing, this process is an appropriate time to make those changes. | New appropriate instance sizes and storage types and sizes are identified for the control plane and worker nodes. |
| 6 | Disable Autoscaler | All type of source clusters | Autoscaling must be disabled for clusters undergoing the takeover process, as it is not currently supported. | Verify that the cluster autoscaler is not running by checking the autoscaler deployment or configuration status. kubectl get deployment cluster-autoscaler \-n kube-system should return No resources found. |
| 7 | Communication | All type of source clusters | Communicate with all relevant teams about the takeover process and with the maintenance windows.  Ensure stakeholders understand the process, and that all contact information is known and available. | Communication sent. |
| 8 | Pause Operations on Source Cluster | All type of source clusters | Ensure no changes are made to the cluster during the takeover. Pause all operations (automated or manual) on the relevant cluster, including potential CI/CD pipelines. | All operations on the Kubernetes cluster are paused. |
| 9 | Source Cluster Backup | All type of source clusters | Perform a full cluster backup using the existing tool and mechanism, ensuring it includes etcd and associated workloads.  | Backup operation is successful. Backup content is available and verified. Restore procedure is documented and understood. |
| **At this point, no further changes should be made to the source cluster. The maintenance window begins here.** |  |  |  |  |

## Takeover Inception {#takeover-inception}

This phase initiates the actual takeover process to integrate the existing cluster into Palette. It involves the cluster registration in Palette.

|  | Steps | Context | Description | Validation |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| 1 | Cluster State Validation | All type of source clusters | Ensure the source cluster is in a healthy state with no critical issues before initiating the takeover process.  | Review any alerts or issues in existing monitoring tools. Verify that all control plane components (API server, scheduler, controller manager) are running smoothly. kubectl get componentstatuses Ensure all nodes are in Ready state. Confirm that all essential pods (in system namespaces) are running without errors or restarts. ETCD status on stacked etcd Ensure resources usage (CPU, memory) are within acceptable limits: kubectl top nodes kubectl top pods \--all-namespaces Inspect logs for any critical errors or warnings: kubectl logs \-n kube-system |
|  | ETCD State Validation | Source clusters with external ETCD | (optional) Ensure the external etcd is in a healthy state with no critical issues before initiating the takeover process. | Check the health of the etcd cluster if it’s running externally: etcdctl cluster-health etcdctl member health etcdctl endpoint health etcdctl endpoint status |
| 2 | Cluster Manifest Preparation |  | Extract the source workload cluster manifests from the source management cluster with drivectl (refer to the steps below in the [Cluster Manifest Preparation](#cluster-manifest-preparation) section).  | Manifest templates are created and stored on the control tower machine. |
| 3 | Cluster Registration |  | Initiate the cluster registration in Palette with the API and the payload modeled (refer to the steps below in the [Cluster Registration in Palette](#cluster-registration-in-palette) section) | Navigate to the Cluster list in the appropriate Project and ensure that the cluster is in Provisioning status (as depicted in the screenshot below). |

### Cluster Registration in Palette {#cluster-registration-in-palette}

To initiate the takeover process, the source cluster must be registered into Palette via API. The easiest way to do so is to go through the cluster creation via the UI and to copy the payload before finishing the configuration.

*Note: You can use any tool of your choice to make the API request, but Postman is a good option.*

1. Start a regular cluster creation.  
2. Select the AWS TKO cloud (created previously).  
3. Enter the name of the cluster (as it will appear in Palette), and complete other relevant information (description, tags, etc.)  
4. Select the appropriate cloud account.  
5. Add the correct infra profile.  
6. In the cluster configuration step:  
   * Enter the appropriate information in the fields to the left and adapt the cluster configuration manifest so that it reflects the running configuration of the source cluster. Use the manifests that were generated in the previous step (*Cluster Manifest Preparation*).  
7. In the nodes configuration step:  
   * Enter the appropriate information in the fields to the left and adapt all the node pool configuration manifests so that they reflect the running configuration of the source cluster. Use the manifests that were generated in the previous step (*Cluster Manifest Preparation*).  
   * Repeat for every pool.  
8. In the cluster settings page:  
   * OS patching \> No  
   * Patch OS on boot \> No  
   * Reboot if required \> No  
   * Scans \> No  
   * Backups \> No  
   * RBAC \> No  
9. Click Validate but don’t select Finish Configuration.  
10. Click on the API button (top right corner) and copy the API payload for the cluster creation.  
11. Edit the payload, and add a new line as first new line in the spec section, as following: “clusterType”: “PureAttach”,

![][image2]

12. Register the cluster with a POST API on: https://\<your-Palette-FQDN\>/v1/spectroclusters/cloudTypes/awstko?ProjectUid=\<your-project-UID\> with the previous modified payload in the body.  
    * *Note: Project UID can be retrieved from the Projects page in Palette.*  
13. Get the cluster UID from the response of the POST request.  
14. The cluster will appear in a Provisioning status in the UI (as depicted in the screenshot below). No further action is required at this step in this phase.

![][image3]

### Cluster Manifest Preparation {#cluster-manifest-preparation}

*Note: those steps must be run from the Linux machine running the takeover steps (a.k.a. control tower machine).*

Connect to the control tower machine and verify that the following prerequisites are met:

* Two Kubeconfig files must be available and ready for use:  
  * One for the source management cluster  
  * One for the source workload cluster  
* Ensure the directory structure follows the guidelines outlined in the *Takeover Control Tower Machine Preparation* section above.

| ⚠️ Set the Kubernetes context to the source management cluster using the relevant Kubeconfig. ⚠️ |  |  |  |
| :---: | ----- | ----- | ----- |

15. Validate your connection to the source management cluster by checking the Kubernetes context.  
16. Using the drivectl CLI, extract the necessary information about the source workload cluster (cluster templates, control plane pool templates, worker node pools) from the management cluster by running the following command. Replace the parameters surrounded by angle brackets accordingly:

drivectl move \-n \<source-cluster-ns-in-mgmt-cluster\> \--clusterName \<source-cluster-name\> \--to-template-directory takeover-templates/\<target-cluster-name-in-palette\>

Where:

* \<source-cluster-ns-in-mgmt-cluster\>: namespace from the source management cluster in which the source workload cluster is configured.  
* \<source-cluster-name\>: source workload cluster name as defined in the source management cluster.  
* \<target-cluster-name-in-palette\>: used to create a local subfolder in the control tower machine to store relevant manifests.

Note: This command applies only to existing CAPI (Cluster API) source clusters.

## Onboarding & Rollout {#onboarding-&-rollout}

This phase includes initializing the source cluster with CAPI, transferring CAPI resources to the workload cluster, applying the agent manifests, and the automatic reconciliation through Palette.

|  | Step | Context | Description | Validation |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
|  | Namespace Creation | All type of source clusters | Create the namespace where the CAPI components and Palette agents will be running. | Namespace is created and annotated accordingly. |
|  | Transfer existing PKI Certificates | Kubeadm-based source clusters | Discover and transfer PKI certificates as secrets. | Secrets are created with appropriate PKIs |
|  | Install CAPI in Source Workload Cluster | All type of source clusters | Using clusterctl, initialize CAPI in the source workload cluster (refer to the steps below in the [Install CAPI in Source Cluster](#install-capi-in-source-workload-cluster) section). Note: this is also required for CAPI-based Kubernetes clusters, where the CAPI components typically run in the management cluster. However, in Palette, the CAPI components are deployed within a namespace in the target cluster. | In source workload cluster: clusterctl output doesn’t present any warnings or errors cert-manager should be present and running CAPI pods are healthy and running in capi-system namespace CAPA pods are healthy and running in capa-system namespace  |
|  | Source IaaS Discovery | Kubeadm-based source clusters | Discovery of source cluster infrastructure components and creation of required objects | ​​Create “Cluster” Object: Include cluster.x-k8s.io/takeover-cluster: "" annotation along with controlPlaneEndpoint discovered from the original cluster. Create “AWSCluster” Object: Include controlPlaneEndpoint and controlPlaneLoadBalancer along with network: securityGroupOverrides, subnets, and VPC information from the original cluster. Apply Other Objects: KCP, AWSMachineTemplate, MachineDeployment, RoleBinding, Service Accounts.  |
|  | Control Plane Nodes Merging | Kubeadm-based source clusters | New control plane nodes will be deployed and joined to the cluster automatically. A series of manual steps will migrate ETCD into a stacked configuration. | Sanity checks for etcd to ensure all data is sync’d to new ETCD nodes (check in ETCD migration demo) |
|  | Control Plane Cleaning | Kubeadm-based source clusters | Old control plane nodes will not automatically be removed, we must cordon, drain, and manually delete them.  | Original control plane nodes removed. |
|  | Pivot | CAPI-based source cluster | Using drivectl, transfer all CAPI resources from the source management cluster to the target namespace in the workload cluster (refer to the steps below in the [Pivot](#pivot) section).  | drivectl doesn’t present any warnings or errors Exit code 0 is expected  |
|  | Agents Deployments | All type of source clusters | Install the necessary Palette agents on the source cluster (refer to the steps below in the [Rollout & Finalization](#rollout-&-finalization) section). After a few minutes, the cluster will be fully adopted by Palette, displaying a Healthy status. | Manifest successfully installed with kubectl (no warnings or errors) No pods crashing Cluster state changes in UI and control plane nodes appear Cluster shows as Healthy and Running in Palette |
|  | Worker Nodes Rollout | Kubeadm-based source clusters | Identify a set of N worker nodes that can be replaced, and do the steps in wiki Attention to: IP availability Storage pool |  |

### Transfer Existing PKI Certificates

*Note: this step only applies for kubeadm-based source cluster.*

Login to control plane node from the source cluster and run the following commands:

kubectl create namespace cluster-\<UID\>

kubectl create secret generic demo-tko-cluster2-kubeconfig \-n cluster-\<UID\> \--from-file=value=/etc/kubernetes/admin.conf \--type=cluster.x-k8s.io/secret  
kubectl label secret demo-tko-cluster2-kubeconfig \-n cluster-\<UID\> cluster.x-k8s.io/cluster-name=demo-tko-cluster2

cd /etc/kubernetes/pki/  
echo "Apply ca.crt"  
kubectl create secret generic demo-tko-cluster2-ca \-n cluster-\<UID\> \--from-file=tls.crt=./ca.crt \--from-file=tls.key=ca.key \--type=[cluster.x-k8s.io/secret](http://cluster.x-k8s.io/secret)

echo "Apply sa.pub"  
kubectl create secret generic demo-tko-cluster2-sa \-n cluster-\<UID\> \--from-file=tls.crt=./sa.pub \--from-file=tls.key=./sa.key \--type=[cluster.x-k8s.io/secret](http://cluster.x-k8s.io/secret)

echo "Apply front-proxy-client.crt"  
kubectl create secret generic demo-tko-cluster2-proxy \-n cluster-\<UID\> \--from-file=tls.crt=./front-proxy-ca.crt \--from-file=tls.key=./front-proxy-ca.key \--type=[cluster.x-k8s.io/secret](http://cluster.x-k8s.io/secret)

echo "Apply etcd"  
kubectl create secret generic demo-tko-cluster2-etcd \-n cluster-\<UID\> \--from-file=tls.crt=./etcd/ca.crt \--from-file=tls.key=./etcd/ca.key \--type=[cluster.x-k8s.io/secret](http://cluster.x-k8s.io/secret)

### Install CAPI in Source Workload Cluster {#install-capi-in-source-workload-cluster}

The objective of this step is to initialize CAPI in the source workload cluster to prepare it for the takeover process into Palette.

Connect to the control tower machine and verify that the following prerequisites are met:

* Two Kubeconfig files must be available and ready for use:  
  * One for the source management cluster  
  * One for the source workload cluster  
* Ensure the directory structure follows the guidelines outlined in the *Takeover Control Tower Machine Preparation* section above.

| ⚠️ Set the Kubernetes context to the source target cluster using the relevant Kubeconfig. ⚠️ |  |  |  |
| :---: | ----- | ----- | ----- |

1. Validate your connection to the source workload cluster by checking the Kubernetes context.  
2. Create a new namespace for the cluster and annotate it using the following commands. Replace *\<UID\>* with the actual UID of the cluster that was registered in Palette via the API:

kubectl create ns cluster-\<UID\>  
kubectl annotate ns cluster-\<UID\> clusterEnv=target

3. Export AWS credentials

export AWS\_ACCESS\_KEY\_ID=  
export AWS\_SECRET\_ACCESS\_KEY=  
export AWS\_SESSION\_TOKEN=  
export AWS\_REGION=eu-west-1  
export AWS\_B64ENCODED\_CREDENTIALS=$(clusterawsadm bootstrap credentials encode-as-profile)

4. Initialize CAPI on the source target cluster by running the following clusterctl command:

clusterctl init \--infrastructure=aws:v2.0.2 \--core cluster-api:v1.5.3 \--control-plane kubeadm:v1.5.3 \--bootstrap kubeadm:v1.5.3 \--config takeover-templates/clusterctl.yaml

Note: These versions have been validated by Spectro Cloud to ensure compatibility with your existing infrastructure and source cluster requirements.

The overrides directory will contain the upstream CAPI manifest that clusterctl will use to install the CAPI stack on the cluster, as the CAPI components are currently running in the management cluster.

### Pivot {#pivot}

Connect to the control tower machine and verify that the following prerequisites are met:

* Two Kubeconfig files must be available and ready for use:  
  * One for the source management cluster  
  * One for the source workload cluster  
* Ensure the directory structure follows the guidelines outlined in the *Takeover Control Tower Machine Preparation* section above.

| ⚠️ Set the Kubernetes context to the source management cluster using the relevant Kubeconfig. ⚠️ |  |  |  |
| :---: | ----- | ----- | ----- |

1. Validate your connection to the source management cluster by checking the Kubernetes context.  
2. Using the drivectl CLI, move the CAPI resources from the management cluster to the newly created namespace in the source workload cluster by running the following command. Replace the parameters surrounded by angle brackets accordingly:

drivectl move \-n \<source-cluster-ns-in-mgmt-cluster\> \--clusterName=\<target-cluster-name-in-palette\> \--to-namespace cluster-\<UID\> \--to-kubeconfig=/complete/path/to/target/workload/cluster/admin.kubeconfig

Where:

* \<source-cluster-ns-in-mgmt-cluster\>: namespace from the source management cluster in which the source workload cluster is configured.  
* \<target-cluster-name-in-palette\>: target cluster name as existing in Palette.

This command searches the source management cluster’s namespace for the specified cluster name and transfers all resources to the target namespace in the workload cluster.

### Rollout & Finalization {#rollout-&-finalization}

Connect to the control tower machine and verify that the following prerequisites are met:

* Two Kubeconfig files must be available and ready for use:  
  * One for the source management cluster  
  * One for the source workload cluster  
* Ensure the directory structure follows the guidelines outlined in the *Takeover Control Tower Machine Preparation* section above.

| ⚠️ Set the Kubernetes context to the source target cluster using the relevant Kubeconfig. ⚠️ |  |  |  |
| :---: | ----- | ----- | ----- |

1. Validate your connection to the source target cluster by checking the Kubernetes context.  
2. Using kubectl, deploy the Palette agents to finalize the takeover by running the following command. Replace \<UID\> with the actual UID of the cluster that was registered in Palette via the API:

kubectl apply \-f https://\<your-Palette-FQDN\>/v1/spectroclusters/\<UID\>/import/manifest

This will install the necessary Palette agents on the source workload cluster and complete the takeover. After a few minutes, the cluster will be fully provisioned in Palette, displaying a Healthy status with all nodes visible.

## Validation & Cleaning {#validation-&-cleaning}

This final phase involves validating the success of the takeover process. It includes thorough testing, ensuring that all workloads and data remain intact and operational, and cleaning up any temporary resources used during the transition. The acceptance tests validate that the cluster has been successfully integrated with Palette.

| Step | Description | Validation |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| 1 | New nodes should be healthy and in running state. | New nodes should come up and show in Ready state. Compare with metrics pre / post takeover |
| 2 | Monitor Capi related Pod logs for issues / Splunk | Errors and Warnings should not be related to Palette / Takeover |
| 3 | Palette and cluster-management-agent are up and running. | Deployments / Replicasets / Pods are all healthy |
| 4 | UI must show cluster in Running status with pack status also reported back as green. | Validate all sections of UI are populated and show relevant data |
| 5 | Fleet Agent Scaled back up / enabled and able to complete a deployment. | Scale fleet-agent replicas back to original setting, or re-enable paused deployments within Fleet UI. |
| 6 | Complete a Backup with original method | Backup should be successful |

Overall Ideas:

* Conduct thorough testing to ensure the cluster functions as expected.  
* The cluster must seamlessly function with all the cluster resources and components, and the customer experience must be identical to a cluster deployed by Palette.  
* Health and status of: cluster, nodes, packs, etc.  
* Cleanup of remaining tkg-related items will be removed by LM after further evaluation.
